        <name>8.1.4.2 (not in quiz): Solving three equations in three unknowns</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p&gt;Use Cramer's rule to find the solution of the system: &lt;br&gt; &lt;br&gt; \[ {@eqns[1]@}\ =\ {@bmat[1,1]@} , \] \[ {@eqns[2]@}\ =\ {@bmat[2,1]@} , \] \[ {@eqns[3]@}\ =\ {@bmat[3,1]@} , \] &lt;br&gt; \(x=\) [[input:ans1]]&amp;nbsp;[[validation:ans1]]&lt;br&gt; \(y=\) [[input:ans2]]&amp;nbsp;[[validation:ans2]]&lt;br&gt; \(z=\) [[input:ans3]]&amp;nbsp;[[validation:ans3]]&lt;br&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;[[feedback:Result]]&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;Cramer's rule states that \(x = \frac{\Delta_{x}}{\Delta}\) where \(\Delta\) is the determinant of the matrix and \(\Delta_{x}\) is the determinant of the matrix with the x column replaced by the numbers on the right hand side of
the equations and similarly \(y = \frac{\Delta_{y}}{\Delta}\) and \(z = \frac{\Delta_{z}}{\Delta}\). &lt;br&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Therefore for the system, &lt;br&gt; \[{@eqns[1]@}\ =\ {@bmat[1,1]@} , \] \[ {@eqns[2]@}\ =\ {@bmat[2,1]@} , \] \[ {@eqns[3]@}\ =\ {@bmat[3,1]@} , \]&lt;br&gt; \[ \Delta = \det{@Amat@}={@D@},\]&lt;br&gt; \[\Delta_{x} = \det{@Amatx@}={@Dx@},\]&lt;br&gt; \[\Delta_{y} = \det{@Amaty@}={@Dy@},\]
    and&lt;br&gt; \[\Delta_{z} = \det{@Amatz@}={@Dz@},\]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;where the notation \(\det A = |A|\) is the determinant of a matrix \(A\).&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt; Hence, \[x=\frac{@Dx@}{@D@} = {@Dx/D@},\] &lt;br&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\[y=\frac{@Dy@}{@D@} = {@Dy/D@},\]&amp;nbsp; and&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; \[z=\frac{@Dz@}{@D@} = {@Dz/D@}.\]&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
